"{\n  \"correct\": \"no\",\n  \"explanation\": \"The code does not correctly handle the mask generation. The mask is generated using torch.randn which can produce negative and positive values. When this mask is multiplied with the image, it can change the pixel values in unintended ways. Typically, a mask should have binary values (0 or 1) where 0 represents the pixel being masked and 1 represents the pixel not being masked. To fix this, we need to modify the mask generation to produce binary values.\",\n  \"patch\": \"8c8\\n< mask = torch.randn(b, 1, h, w).to(device=img.device)\\n---\\n> mask = (torch.randn(b, 1, h, w).to(device=img.device) > 0).float()\\n\"\n}"